Package com.intellij.codeInsight.lookup

Class LookupElement

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.intellij.openapi.util.UserDataHolderBase
      • com.intellij.codeInsight.lookup.LookupElement
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    UserDataHolder, UserDataHolderEx
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ChainCompletionNewVariableLookupElement, EmptyLookupItem, ExpressionLookupItem, ExternalProjectPathLookupElement, FilePathCompletionContributor.FilePathLookupItem, FunctionLookup, JavaGlobalMemberLookupElement, KeywordLookupItem, LiveTemplateLookupElement, LookupElementBuilder, LookupElementDecorator, MutableLookupElement, NamespaceLookup, PackageLookupItem, PsiTypeCanonicalLookupElement, PythonLookupElement, SimpleMethodCallLookupElement

    public abstract class LookupElement
extends UserDataHolderBase
    A typical way to create lookup element is to use LookupElementBuilder. Another way is to subclass it. Use the latter way only if you need it to implement some additional interface, to modify equals/hashCode or other advanced logic.
    See Also:
    PrioritizedLookupElement

      • isWorthShowingInAutoPopup

        public boolean isWorthShowingInAutoPopup()
        Invoked when the completion autopopup contains only the items that exactly match the user-entered prefix to determine whether the popup should be closed to not get in the way when navigating through the code. Should return true if there's some meaningful information in this item's presentation that the user will miss if the autopopup is suddenly closed automatically. Java method parameters are a good example. For simple variables, there's nothing else interesting besides the variable name which is already entered in the editor, so the autopopup may be closed.
